<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-303-656  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 303 656.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  May 22 1989 n249 p36(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Colo. Legislature fails to extend program that reduces rates forlow-income users. (the Colorado telephone lifeline program)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rockwell, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Colorado Legislature did not vote for the permanentcontinuation of a lifeline service that cuts telephone linecharges for low-income subscribers The shutting down of theprogram will effect some 17,000 low-income customers and willtranslate into a $6 per month rate increase.andP;  A US Westspokeswoman noted that Colorado was the only state were thelegislature became involved in setting rates, normally a functionof the state public utilities commission, and that deregulatorylegislation was not a factor.andP;  Some legislators saw the program,which is funded by ratepayers, as a form of consumer taxation.andP;  USWest remained hopeful that other options for keeping the programalive could be pursued, viewing the dismantling of the program asa last resort.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   U S West Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    USW.andO;Topic:     ColoradoLegislationCommunications Service SuppliersTrendsTelephones.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Percentage of Families with a Telephone by Family Income: March89. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>